Yum!!!!  Last minute decided to come here for dinner and snagged an early dinner reservation for right after opening. The place was pretty empty (5:45p Saturday) but it filled up by the time we left.  I got the braised lamb ravioli and my friends both got the seafood linguini.  Braised Lamb ravioli - I got this with the intention of being adventurous, as I'm not a lamb person. I've only recently started to be willing to eat lamb (not a fan of how gamey it usually tastes). Well, the ravioli was awesome. It didn't taste very gamey and the flavor of the sauce was rich but not heavy. I wish it could have been a little spicy but it was still delicious as is.  Seafood linguini - I've literally never seen that much seafood on a plate of seafood pasta. Half a lobster tail and that many mussels?? For less than $30?? Pleasantly unexpected. I only had two bites of it, and it was well seasoned and the pasta was perfectly al dente. My friends were really pleased with the amount of seafood they got.  One thing that could be improved is the bread that they served at the beginning - it was a bit stale, and I wish they had given us balsamic vinegar along with the olive oil.  I would definitely come back here, maybe with a bigger appetite so I could try more things on the menu.

This place was incredible, from the moment we walked in until the moment we left. The waiter explained a long list of specials from memory, and another server noticed I bumped a utensil off the table and showed up a couple minutes later with a fresh (hot) fork and knife for me (whoops! Guess they saw that one). My gluten free questions were all answered on the spot. Plus, everyone seemed genuinely happy to be there. Oh, and the food!! Oh my god, the food was so incredible. Both were crazy flavorful and just out of this world.  Highly recommend!!!

This is one of my favorite restaurants. It is a restaurant to bring good friends or out of town guests for a quiet, leisurely meal where you can catch up and not worry about the waiter trying to rush you out for the next seating.  In fact Tortino is a very "neighborhoody" place to the point that you know most the waiters by their first names and they know you.  Food is absolutely and always delicious.  The soup specials never disapoint. Tonight I had cauliflower soup with shrimp. My main course was the daily risotto, this time with porcini mushrooms and 4 cheeses. I also tried my sister's grilled salmon and my mother's papardelle with chicken and mushrooms. Everything is very good.  The asparagus and carrots with the salmon were cooked just right and a little crunchy. Not soggy or overcooked. For dessert, ask if they have their handmade cannolli available (not on the menu), although I like their Pana cotta with berries too.

My boyfriend wouldn't stop talking about the roasted chicken throughout the whole meal. We saw an entree on their website that wasn't on the dinner menu and they made it for us. It was one of the best meals we have ever had. I really recommend this quaint little restaurant for a nice date for 2 😀

5 star authentic Italian food with 3 star prices. Classy, romantic, ambient music superb. Don't need to go to Italy to savor what real top level Italian food is all about. I'm coming back soon all the way from Miami FL.

The spinach Tagliatelle with chicken was just right.  Finally, the Roasted Veal Tenderloin was served medium rare as requested served over au gratin potatoes with a Black Truffle reduction.  The couple  next to us raved about the grilled pork chops.  So don't  go anywhere else before Tortino.  By the way, very reasonably priced.

My friend ordered the special, lobster ravioli and the cream was exceptional; have to say it is one of the best ravioli we ever had. I had the pan seared duck breast and the dressing was superb as well as the tenderness of the meat. The server recommended us the chocolate cake for dessert; it was not bad. The cocktails are lower than average though, plain and not interesting at all. Our overall dining experience was great. Note: not a very quiet place if you want a place for conversation.

However, we just wanted to order a starter to kill the time. As opposed to their not very welcoming servers, the quality of food and the potions were pleasantly satisfying. It was possibly the worst excuse for Italian food I've ever experienced! The restrooms even had blowers to dry your hands. Something you'd expect at a Denny's perhaps. The food was bad! The reviews I read were misleading and inaccurate. If you are looking for even mediocre Italian food, you won't find it at Tortino.  The waiter compared a white fish special ( likely Bassa farmed fish) to Sea Bass. That was simply a lie!  The lamb chop which was good meat, unlike the old and bad fish, wasn't marinated,  and therefore tough as leather, and tasteless as well.  The wine we ordered was great! And, reasonably priced. But as a dining experiences go this was a disaster!  If you are looking for a reasonable Italian food experience in Washington, D.C. DO NOT GO TO TORTINO!  You will be disappointed.
